<br>
Most supercomputers built in the past were fast because they could essentially add/multiply an entire table of numbers to produce a table of results in about the same time a normal processor could add/multiply only once for a single result.  They crunched assloads of numbers fast and had millions of dollars of super-fast memory (95% of the computer's cost) but nothing else.  Still that supercomputer was logically doing only one thing at a time.  <br>
<br>
